ABSTRACT

The project aims to create a deep learning model that can take audio data and classify it based on the emotion presented by the speaker. This was done by taking an already fine-tuned Wav2Vec model and further fine-tuning it on a dataset more than 2x the original one. The datasets involved are RAVDESS, TESS, and CREMA-D, all open source audio datasets that were developed for this very purpose.

With the new fine-tuned model, the researchers were able to achieve an 85% test accuracy--wherein the original test accuracy with the original model was only around 60%. The project demonstrates the value of fine-tuning an existing state-of-the-art model on a larger dataset.

INTRODUCTION

Emotion classification from audio is a critical task in areas such as human-computer interaction, sentiment analysis, and behavioral studies. The challenge lies in accurately identifying and categorizing emotions conveyed through speech, which can vary significantly across different speakers and contexts.

"Emotion is the cornerstone of human interactions. In fact, the manner in which something is said can convey just as much information as the words being spoken. Emotional cues in speech are conveyed through vocal inflections known as prosody. Key attributes of prosody include the relative pitch, duration, and intensity of the speech signal." [1]

Audio features like mel spectrograms and MFCCs are instrumental in capturing these attributes. A mel spectrogram visualizes how the frequency content of speech varies over time, reflecting changes in pitch and intensity. MFCCs, on the other hand, summarize the timbral characteristics of the audio, which helps in capturing subtle variations in pitch and emotional tone. These features enable the effective analysis and classification of emotional cues in speech.

PROBLEM STATEMENT AND MOTICATION

How can we use audio data to classify emotions?

The primary objective of this study is to explore effective methods for classifying emotions using audio data. The analysis compares traditional feature extraction techniques against modern deep learning-based audio embeddings, with a particular focus on the application of the Wav2Vec model. The goal is to determine which approach offers superior accuracy and reliability in emotion classification tasks.

Some practical use cases include:

METHODOLOGY

In [6]:
Image(filename=HOME_DIR + 'images/Methodology.PNG', width=1080)
Out[6]:

1. Data Preprocessing

  • Prepare and organize the audio data by combining multiple datasets, ensuring that all labels and filepaths are accurate and consistent. Given the importance of pitch, duration, and intensity, avoid data augmentation that could distort these features.

2. Feature Extraction

  • Convert raw audio into a form that models can use. Two approaches are explored:
    • Traditional Features - Techniques such as mel spectrograms, MFCCs, and pitch analysis are used to manually extract features that capture the characteristics of the audio signal.
    • Audio Embeddings with Wav2Vec - A modern approach that uses the Wav2Vec model to automatically learn and generate embeddings directly from the raw audio, capturing more nuanced aspects of the sound.

3. Model Training and Finetuning

  • CLSTM (Convolutional LSTM) Model: Trained on traditional features, this model combines convolutional layers to capture local patterns with LSTM layers to handle the temporal dynamics of the audio.
  • Pretrained Wav2Vec Model: This model uses embeddings from the Wav2Vec model and fine-tunes them on the specific task of emotion classification, leveraging pre-learned audio representations. Description

4. Evaluation

  • Evaluate models based on their accuracy in classifying emotions, allowing for a direct comparison of the effectiveness of the CLSTM model versus the pretrained Wav2Vec model.

SCOPE AND LIMITATION

  • The study is limited to audio data and may not account for multimodal aspects of emotion classification.

  • Results may vary depending on the quality and representativeness of the datasets used, especially since they are from actors and may not fully capture everyday speech nuances.

  • The effectiveness of the Wav2Vec model and CLSTM model is evaluated solely based on emotion classification accuracy, which may not cover other relevant performance metrics or practical considerations in real-world applications.

DATASETS

The datasets used are open-source audio emotion classification datasets available online: RAVDESS, CREMA-D, and TESS. They consist of recordings with diverse emotional expressions and are publicly available for research and development purposes. The datasets are extracted from ZIP files and organized into specific directories for ease of use.

Ryerson Audio-Visual Database of Emotional Speech and Song (RAVDESS) Dataset

The RAVDESS dataset provides 1440 audio files from 24 professional actors (12 female, 12 male) for emotion classification, with filenames encoded to include modality, vocal channel, emotion, emotional intensity, statement, repetition, and actor information. [2][3][4]

  • Modality (01 = full-AV, 02 = video-only, 03 = audio-only).
  • Vocal channel (01 = speech, 02 = song).
  • Emotion (01 = neutral, 02 = calm, 03 = happy, 04 = sad, 05 = angry, 06 = fearful, 07 = disgust, 08 = surprised).
  • Emotional intensity (01 = normal, 02 = strong). NOTE: There is no strong intensity for the 'neutral' emotion.
  • Statement (01 = "Kids are talking by the door", 02 = "Dogs are sitting by the door").
  • Repetition (01 = 1st repetition, 02 = 2nd repetition).
  • Actor (01 to 24. Odd numbered actors are male, even numbered actors are female).

Toronto Emotional Speech Set (TESS) Dataset

The TESS dataset provides 2800 audio files from 2 female actors for emotion classification, with filenames indicating the emotional content. [5]

Crowd Sourced Emotional Multimodal Actors Dataset (CREMA-D) Dataset

CREMA-D is a data set of 7,442 original clips from 91 actors. These clips were from 48 male and 43 female actors between the ages of 20 and 74 coming from a variety of races and ethnicities (African America, Asian, Caucasian, Hispanic, and Unspecified). Actors spoke from a selection of 12 sentences. The sentences were presented using one of six different emotions (Anger, Disgust, Fear, Happy, Neutral, and Sad) and four different emotion levels (Low, Medium, High, and Unspecified). [6]

MODEL AND FEATURE EXTRACTION

TRADITIONAL EXTRACTION¶

For emotion classification, several traditional audio features are extracted to capture different aspects of the speech signal:

  • Zero Crossing Rate (ZCR): Measures how often the signal crosses zero, distinguishing voiced from unvoiced speech and identifying emotions with abrupt changes.

  • Root Mean Square Energy (RMSE): Represents the signal's energy or loudness, helping to detect emotions with varying energy levels.

  • Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCC): Provides a detailed spectral representation of the signal, capturing timbral and phonetic characteristics affected by emotions.

  • Spectral Centroid: Indicates the "center of mass" of the spectrum.

  • Spectral Bandwidth: Measures the width of the spectrum.

  • Spectral Contrast: Captures the difference in amplitude between peaks and valleys in the sound spectrum.

  • Tonnetz: Represents the harmonic relations in music.

  • Chromagram: Analyzes the energy distribution of pitch classes.


librosa is used to compute these features from audio files. Each feature is extracted and combined into a comprehensive feature vector. These vectors are then used to build datasets for training emotion classification models. [7][8] 


# CODE REFERENCE
def zcr(data,frame_length,hop_length):
  zcr=librosa.feature.zero_crossing_rate(data,frame_length=frame_length,hop_length=hop_length)
  return np.squeeze(zcr)

def rmse(data,frame_length=2048,hop_length=512):
  rmse=librosa.feature.rms(y=data,frame_length=frame_length,hop_length=hop_length)
  return np.squeeze(rmse)

def mfcc(data,sr,frame_length=2048,hop_length=512,flatten:bool=True):
  mfcc=librosa.feature.mfcc(y=data,sr=sr)
  return np.squeeze(mfcc.T)if not flatten else np.ravel(mfcc.T)

def spectral_centroid(data, sr, frame_length=2048, hop_length=512):
  centroid = librosa.feature.spectral_centroid(y=data, sr=sr, n_fft=frame_length, hop_length=hop_length)
  return np.squeeze(centroid)

def spectral_bandwidth(data, sr, frame_length=2048, hop_length=512):
  bandwidth = librosa.feature.spectral_bandwidth(y=data, sr=sr, n_fft=frame_length, hop_length=hop_length)
  return np.squeeze(bandwidth)

def spectral_contrast(data, sr, frame_length=2048, hop_length=512,flatten:bool=True):
  contrast = librosa.feature.spectral_contrast(y=data, sr=sr, n_fft=frame_length, hop_length=hop_length, fmin=60.0, n_bands=2)
  return np.squeeze(contrast.T) if not flatten else np.ravel(contrast.T)

def tonnetz(data, sr,flatten:bool=True):
  tonnetz = librosa.feature.tonnetz(y=data, sr=sr, fmin=5, bins_per_octave=12)
  return np.squeeze(tonnetz.T) if not flatten else np.ravel(tonnetz.T)

def chromagram(data, sr, frame_length=2048, hop_length=512,flatten:bool=True):
  chromagram = librosa.feature.chroma_cens(y=data, sr=sr, fmin=5, bins_per_octave=12)
  return np.squeeze(chromagram.T) if not flatten else np.ravel(chromagram.T)

def mel_spectrogram(data, sr, frame_length=2048, hop_length=512, flatten: bool=True):
  mel = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(y=data, sr=sr, n_fft=frame_length, hop_length=hop_length)
  return np.squeeze(mel.T) if not flatten else np.ravel(mel.T)

def extract_features(data,sr=22050,frame_length=2048,hop_length=512):
    result=np.array([])
    result=np.hstack((result,
                      spectral_contrast(data,frame_length,hop_length),
                      tonnetz(data,frame_length),
                      chromagram(data,frame_length,hop_length),
                      mfcc(data,sr,frame_length,hop_length),
                      zcr(data,frame_length,hop_length),
                      rmse(data,frame_length,hop_length),
                      spectral_centroid(data,frame_length,hop_length),
                      spectral_bandwidth(data,frame_length,hop_length)
                     ))
    return result

def get_features(path,duration=3, offset=0):
  data,sr=librosa.load(path,duration=duration,offset=offset)
  aud=extract_features(data)
  audio=np.array(aud)

  return [audio]

# PROCESS FEATURE EXTRACTION
X,Y=[],[]
for path,emotion,index in tqdm (zip(data_path.Path,data_path.Emotions,range(data_path.Path.shape[0]))):
  try:
    features=get_features(path)
    if index%500==0:
      print(f'{index} audio has been processed')
    for i in features:
      X.append(i)
      Y.append(emotion)
  except:
    pass
print('Done')

features_df = pd.DataFrame(X)
features_df['Emotions'] = Y

CLSTM Model¶

The CLSTM model combines Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, which are particularly effective for tasks involving sequential data, such as audio signals. The idea is that by integrating CNNs with LSTMs, the CLSTM model can effectively capture both spatial (spectral) features and temporal (sequential) dependencies in audio data.[9]

AUDIO EMBEDDINGS (WAV2VEC)¶

Wav2Vec is a model architecture developed by Facebook AI for processing raw audio data. It is based on a self-supervised learning framework that enables the model to learn meaningful representations from audio without the need for labeled data. These representations, known as audio embeddings, are dense vectors that capture the essential features of the audio input.

Wav2Vec is pre-trained on large amounts of unlabeled audio data using a self-supervised learning objective. The model learns to predict masked portions of the audio signal from the surrounding context, which helps it develop a deep understanding of the audio's structure and content.

Pre-trained Model¶

By leveraging a pre-trained model, the emotion recognition system benefits from the knowledge acquired from vast amounts of audio data.

Audio files are limited to 3 seconds in duration, sampled at 16,000 Hz, and processed in batches of 8. The model is designed to recognize 6 emotion classes and outputs features in a 768-dimensional space, which aligns with the Wav2Vec 2.0 architecture.

A pretrained model from Hugging Face is used to streamline the process of speech emotion recognition. By utilizing the r-f/wav2vec-english-speech-emotion-recognition checkpoint, this model leverages prior training on extensive speech data, enabling it to effectively identify and classify emotions in English speech. This approach significantly enhances accuracy and reduces the need for extensive training from scratch.

class Wav2Vec2ForSpeechClassification(nn.Module, PyTorchModelHubMixin):
    def __init__(self, config):
        super(Wav2Vec2ForSpeechClassification, self).__init__()
        self.wav2vec2 = Wav2Vec2Model(config)

        self.classifier = nn.ModuleDict({
            'dense': nn.Linear(config.hidden_size, config.hidden_size),
            'activation': nn.ReLU(),
            'dropout': nn.Dropout(config.final_dropout),
            'out_proj': nn.Linear(config.hidden_size, config.num_labels)
        })

    def forward(self, input_values):
        outputs = self.wav2vec2(input_values)
        hidden_states = outputs.last_hidden_state

        x = self.classifier['dense'](hidden_states[:, 0, :])
        x = self.classifier['activation'](x)
        x = self.classifier['dropout'](x)
        logits = self.classifier['out_proj'](x)

        return logits

TRAIN/TEST SPLIT

CLSTM Train Test Split¶

The dataset is split into training and testing sets for the CLSTM model. Initially, missing values in the feature data are filled with zeros to ensure consistency. The features (X) and labels (Y) are extracted from the features_df DataFrame. The labels are one-hot encoded to prepare them for classification.

  • Feature Extraction: The input features are taken from all columns except the last, and the labels are extracted from the 'Emotions' column.
  • One-Hot Encoding: The labels are transformed into a one-hot encoded format to facilitate multi-class classification.
  • Data Splitting: The dataset is split into training and testing sets using an 80/20 ratio. The data is shuffled and split, with the random_state set for reproducibility.
  • Reshaping: The training and testing data are reshaped to be suitable for LSTM input, with each sample being reshaped into a 3D tensor with one feature channel.
# Pad Audio
features_df=features_df.fillna(0)

# Train test split for CLSTM
X = features_df.iloc[: ,:-1].values
Y = features_df['Emotions'].values

# Encode Y
oe = OneHotEncoder()
Y = oe.fit_transform(np.array(Y).reshape(-1,1)).toarray()

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=42,test_size=0.2, shuffle=True)

Wav2Vec Train/Test Split¶

The dataset is split into training and testing sets for the Wav2Vec model. Here, audio features are extracted and processed to prepare for training with the Wav2Vec model.

  • Feature Extraction: The feature_extractor function processes audio data arrays into features suitable for input into the Wav2Vec model. It includes padding and truncation to standardize the length of audio samples.
  • Tensor Conversion: The extracted features and labels are converted into PyTorch tensors and moved to the appropriate device (CPU/GPU) for model training.
  • Dataset Creation: The CustomDataset class is defined to handle the input features and labels. This dataset class includes methods for retrieving data samples and their corresponding labels and lengths.
  • DataLoader Creation: The DataLoader class is used to create data loaders for both training and evaluation datasets. These loaders handle batching, shuffling, and parallel data loading to optimize training efficiency.
# Define CustomDataset
class CustomDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, inputs, labels, label_lengths):
        self.inputs = inputs
        self.labels = labels
        self.label_lengths = label_lengths

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.inputs)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        return {
            'input_values': self.inputs[idx],
            'labels': self.labels[idx],
            'label_lengths': self.label_lengths[idx]
        }

FINETUNING (WAV2VEC)

The Wav2Vec finetuning process involves several key steps. First, the model is moved to a GPU if available to speed up computations. An AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of 2e-5 is used for parameter updates, and CrossEntropyLoss is employed to measure the model's performance.

Note that the model checkpoint was trained on:

  • Ryerson Audio-Visual Database of Emotional Speech and Song (RAVDESS) - 1440 audio files from 24 professional actors (12 female, 12 male)
  • Toronto emotional speech set (TESS) - 2800 audio files from 2 female actors
  • Crowd Sourced Emotional Multimodal Actors Dataset (CREMA-D) - CREMA-D is a data set of 7,442 original clips from 91 actors. These clips were from 48 male and 43 female actors between the ages of 20 and 74 coming from a variety of races and ethnicities (African America, Asian, Caucasian, Hispanic, and Unspecified). Actors spoke from a selection of 12 sentences. The sentences were presented using one of six different emotions (Anger, Disgust, Fear, Happy, Neutral, and Sad) and four different emotion levels (Low, Medium, High, and Unspecified).

In contrast, our finetuned model is trained on the three entire datasets, totalling almost 11,000 data points versus the original 4720 data points. Hence, we are increasing the train set in order to improve generalization.

# Move model to GPU if available
device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
model.to(device)

torch.cuda.empty_cache()

# Initialize optimizer
optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=2e-5)

# Define loss function
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

# Define accuracy computation function
def compute_accuracy(predictions, labels):
    _, predicted = torch.max(predictions, 1)
    correct = (predicted == labels).sum().item()
    total = labels.size(0)
    return correct / total

# Training function
def train(model, data_loader, optimizer, device, accuracy_history):
    model.train()
    total_loss = 0
    correct_predictions = 0
    total_samples = 0

    for batch in tqdm(data_loader, desc="Training"):
        # Move data to the same device as the model
        input_values = batch['input_values'].to(device)
        labels = batch['labels'].to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # Forward pass
        outputs = model(input_values=input_values)  # Assumes model returns logits
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

        # Backward pass and optimization
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        total_loss += loss.item()

        # Compute accuracy
        accuracy = compute_accuracy(outputs, labels)
        correct_predictions += (torch.max(outputs, 1)[1] == labels).sum().item()
        total_samples += labels.size(0)

    avg_loss = total_loss / len(data_loader)
    avg_accuracy = correct_predictions / total_samples
    accuracy_history.append(avg_accuracy)
    print(f"Training Loss: {avg_loss}, Accuracy: {avg_accuracy}")

# Evaluation function
def evaluate(model, data_loader, device, accuracy_history):
    model.eval()
    total_loss = 0
    correct_predictions = 0
    total_samples = 0

    with torch.no_grad():
        for batch in tqdm(data_loader, desc="Evaluating"):
            # Move data to the same device as the model
            input_values = batch['input_values'].to(device)
            labels = batch['labels'].to(device)

            # Forward pass
            outputs = model(input_values=input_values)  # Assumes model returns logits
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

            total_loss += loss.item()

            # Compute accuracy
            accuracy = compute_accuracy(outputs, labels)
            correct_predictions += (torch.max(outputs, 1)[1] == labels).sum().item()
            total_samples += labels.size(0)

    avg_loss = total_loss / len(data_loader)
    avg_accuracy = correct_predictions / total_samples
    accuracy_history.append(avg_accuracy)
    print(f"Evaluation Loss: {avg_loss}, Accuracy: {avg_accuracy}")

# Initialize accuracy history lists
train_accuracy_history = []
eval_accuracy_history = []

epochs = 3
# Training and evaluation loop
for epoch in range(epochs):  # Number of epochs
    print(f"Epoch {epoch + 1}")
    train(model, train_loader, optimizer, device, train_accuracy_history)
    evaluate(model, eval_loader, device, eval_accuracy_history)

INFERENCE / DEMO APPLICATION

The demo application loads the trained model (model_finetuned.pth) and includes an audio component that records real-time audio. Every 10 seconds, the app samples the first 3 seconds of the audio, resamples it to 16,000 samples per second (as the model was trained on that rate), then extracts features using Wav2Vec2. The extracted features are then fed to the model for inference, where the logits that were produced by the model are passed through a softmax function to convert them into probabilities representing the likelihood of each emotion. These probabilities are mapped to corresponding emotion labels through a predefined mapping.

app.py¶

import gradio as gr
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from PIL import Image
import librosa
import time
from datetime import datetime
import pandas as pd
import torch
import torch.nn.functional as F
from tqdm import tqdm
from transformers import Wav2Vec2Config, Wav2Vec2Model
import torch.nn as nn
from huggingface_hub import PyTorchModelHubMixin, hf_hub_download
import json
from transformers import Wav2Vec2FeatureExtractor, Wav2Vec2Processor

# Define constants and paths
HOME_DIR = ""
local_config_path = 'config.json'
local_preprocessor_config_path = 'preprocessor_config.json'
local_weights_path = 'pytorch_model.bin'
local_training_args_path = 'training_args.bin'

# Define the id2label mapping
id2label = {
    0: "angry",
    1: "disgust",
    2: "fear",
    3: "happy",
    4: "neutral",
    5: "sad",
    6: "surprise"
}

# Define the prediction function
def predict(model, feature_extractor, data, max_length, id2label):
    # Extract features
    print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), ":Extracting features...")
    inputs = feature_extractor(data,
                               sampling_rate=16000,
                               max_length=max_length,
                               return_tensors='tf',
                               padding=True,
                               truncation=True)
    torch_inputs = torch.tensor(inputs['input_values'].numpy(), dtype=torch.float32)

    print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), ":Predicting...")
    # Forward pass
    outputs = model(input_values=torch_inputs)

    # Extract logits from the output
    logits = outputs

    # Apply softmax to get probabilities
    probabilities = F.softmax(logits, dim=-1)

    # Get the predicted class index
    predicted_class_idx = torch.argmax(probabilities, dim=-1).item()
    predicted_label = id2label[predicted_class_idx]

    return predicted_label, probabilities

# Define the Wav2Vec2 model class
class Wav2Vec2ForSpeechClassification(nn.Module, PyTorchModelHubMixin):
    def __init__(self, config):
        super(Wav2Vec2ForSpeechClassification, self).__init__()
        self.wav2vec2 = Wav2Vec2Model(config)

        self.classifier = nn.ModuleDict({
            'dense': nn.Linear(config.hidden_size, config.hidden_size),
            'activation': nn.ReLU(),
            'dropout': nn.Dropout(config.final_dropout),
            'out_proj': nn.Linear(config.hidden_size, config.num_labels)
        })

    def forward(self, input_values):
        outputs = self.wav2vec2(input_values)
        hidden_states = outputs.last_hidden_state

        x = self.classifier['dense'](hidden_states[:, 0, :])
        x = self.classifier['activation'](x)
        x = self.classifier['dropout'](x)
        logits = self.classifier['out_proj'](x)

        return logits

# Load the preprocessor configuration
with open(local_preprocessor_config_path, 'r') as file:
    preprocessor_config = json.load(file)

# Initialize the preprocessor
feature_extractor = Wav2Vec2FeatureExtractor(
    do_normalize=preprocessor_config["do_normalize"],
    feature_extractor_type=preprocessor_config["feature_extractor_type"],
    feature_size=preprocessor_config["feature_size"],
    padding_side=preprocessor_config["padding_side"],
    padding_value=preprocessor_config["padding_value"],
    processor_class_from_name=preprocessor_config["processor_class"],
    return_attention_mask=preprocessor_config["return_attention_mask"],
    sampling_rate=preprocessor_config["sampling_rate"]
)

# Load the finetuned model from Huggingface Hub
model_path = hf_hub_download(
    repo_id="kvilla/wav2vec-english-speech-emotion-recognition-finetuned",
    filename="model_finetuned.pth"

# Load the model
saved_model = torch.load(model_path, map_location=torch.device('cpu'))

# Create and initialize the model
config = Wav2Vec2Config.from_pretrained(local_config_path)
model = Wav2Vec2ForSpeechClassification(config=config)
model.load_state_dict(saved_model)
model.eval()

print("Model initialized successfully.")

# Define the emotion recognition function
def recognize_emotion(audio):
    # Load the audio file using librosa
    sample_rate, audio_data = audio

    # Ensure audio data is in floating-point format
    if not np.issubdtype(audio_data.dtype, np.floating):
        audio_data = audio_data.astype(np.float32)

    # Resample if necessary
    if sample_rate != 16000:
        print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), ":Resampling audio...")
        audio_data = librosa.resample(audio_data,
                                      orig_sr=sample_rate,
                                      target_sr=16000)

    # Predict the emotion
    emotion, probabilities = predict(model,
                                     feature_extractor,
                                     audio_data,
                                     48000, # Limit to 3s 16000 samples x 3
                                     id2label)

    print(probabilities)
    probs = probabilities.detach().numpy().flatten().tolist()

    # Convert probabilities to percentages
    percentages = [round(prob * 100, 2) for prob in probs]

    # Define the class labels
    labels = ["angry", "disgust", "fear", "happy", "neutral", "sad", "surprise"]

    # Create a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame({"Emotion": labels, "Probability (%)": percentages})
    df = df.sort_values(by="Probability (%)", ascending=False)

    print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), df)

    return emotion, get_emotion_image(emotion), df

# Define the function to get the emotion image
def get_emotion_image(emotion):
    emotion_to_image = {
        "angry": "angry.jpeg",
        "disgust": "disgust.jpeg",
        "fear": "fear.jpeg",
        "happy": "happy.jpeg",
        "neutral": "neutral.jpeg",
        "sad": "sad.jpeg",
        "surprise": "surprise.jpeg"
    }

    image_path = emotion_to_image.get(emotion, "default.jpg")
    return Image.open(image_path)

# Create Gradio interface
demo = gr.Blocks()
with demo:
    df_logs = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Timestamp', 'Emotion'])
    theme = gr.themes.Soft(),
    audio_input = gr.Audio(type="numpy",
                            sources=["microphone"],
                            show_label=True,
                            streaming=True
                            )
    text_output = gr.Textbox(label="Recognized Emotion")
    output_df = gr.DataFrame(label="Emotion Probabilities")
    image_output = gr.Image(label="Emotion Image", scale = 1, interactive = False)
    df_logs = gr.DataFrame(label="Output Logs", headers = ['Timestamp', 'Emotion'])

    # Define the process function
    def process_audio(audio, emotion, image, state, df_probs, df_logs):
        current_time = time.time()
        if state is None or (current_time - state >= 10):
            state = current_time
            emotion, image, df_probs = recognize_emotion(audio)

            timestamp = datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
            new_row = {'Timestamp': timestamp, 'Emotion': emotion}

            df_logs = pd.concat([df_logs, pd.DataFrame([new_row])], ignore_index=True)
            print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), "Predicted emotion: ", emotion)

            return emotion, image, state, df_probs, df_logs
        else:
            print(datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d%H:%M:%S'), "Not yet time")
            return emotion, image, state, df_probs, df_logs

    state = gr.State(None)
    audio_input.stream(fn=process_audio, inputs=[audio_input,
                                                 text_output,
                                                 image_output,
                                                 state,
                                                 output_df,
                                                 df_logs],
                       outputs=[text_output,
                                image_output,
                                state,
                                output_df,
                                df_logs])

# Launch Gradio demo
demo.launch(share=True)

The Gradio interface in this application serves as an intuitive and user-friendly platform for real-time emotion recognition based on audio input. The interface is built using gr.Blocks, which allows for the flexible arrangement of components like audio inputs, text outputs, dataframes, and images. The audio_input component captures live audio from the user’s microphone, while the text_output, output_df, and image_output components are designed to display the recognized emotion, the corresponding probabilities for each emotion, and an image representing the predicted emotion, respectively.

The audio_input component captures live audio from the user’s microphone, while the text_output, output_df, and image_output components are designed to display the recognized emotion, the corresponding probabilities for each emotion, and an image representing the predicted emotion, respectively.

The interface is designed to stream the audio input and automatically trigger the emotion recognition process every 10 seconds. This is managed through a process_audio function that handles the logic for when to sample the audio, perform inference using the loaded Wav2Vec2 model, and update the output components with the prediction results. A key feature of this Gradio interface is the logging functionality, where each emotion prediction is timestamped and stored in a log, providing a record of the inferences made during the session. This setup leverages Gradio’s capabilities to create an interactive and engaging experience for users, allowing them to easily test and observe the model’s predictions in real-time.

The demo application was then deployed on Hugging Face Spaces, allowing users to test and interact with the application directly.

CONCLUSION

The evaluation of the pretrained model, wav2vec-english-speech-emotion-recognition, and our finetuned model across various datasets yielded the following accuracies:

  • For the RAVDESS and TESS datasets, our model achieved an accuracy of 99%, slightly outperforming the pretrained model, which achieved 97%.
  • On the CREMA-D dataset, the pretrained model showed a significant drop in performance with an accuracy of 42%, whereas our model performed substantially better, achieving 85%.
  • When evaluated on the combined RAVDESS, TESS, and CREMA-D datasets, our model attained an accuracy of 86%, surpassing the pretrained model’s accuracy of 63%.

Table 7: Evaluation of Pre-trained Wav2Vec Model vs. Finetuned Model
Test Set wav2vec-english-speech-emotion-recognition Finetuned Model
RAVDESS, TESS 97% 99%
CREMA-D 42% 85%
RAVDESS, TESS, CREMA-D 63% 86%

Note: The test sets used for evaluating the model were not part of the training process. They were exclusively reserved for assessing the model’s performance, ensuring an unbiased evaluation of its ability to generalize to new, unseen data.

RECOMMENDATION

  1. Enhance the Dataset / Use Case: Multilingual Customer Support, Cross-Cultural Research

    • Non-American Actors: Including audio from actors with various accents and dialects will enhance the model’s ability to understand and accurately interpret emotions in global customer interactions. This is particularly important for customer support systems deployed in diverse regions where users might speak with different accents.
    • Varied Accents and Dialects: In studies involving cross-cultural research, having a dataset with diverse speech patterns ensures that emotional analyses are culturally sensitive and accurate. This is crucial for research aimed at understanding emotional expression across different cultures.

  2. Adopt a Multi-Modal Approach / Use Case: Interactive Virtual Assistants, Therapy and Counseling

    • Facial Expressions: For virtual assistants or chatbots, integrating facial expression analysis can improve the system’s ability to respond appropriately to users' emotional states. For instance, an assistant that recognizes when a user is frustrated or happy based on both voice and facial cues can tailor responses more effectively.
    • Contextual Information: In therapeutic applications, combining audio with visual and contextual data can provide a more holistic understanding of a client's emotional state. This integration helps therapists better gauge emotions during sessions, leading to more personalized and effective interventions.

To enhance model performance, various strategies can be implemented.

  • Improving Data Augmentation is crucial, particularly for real-world audio processing where noise injection ensures accuracy in noisy environments like smart home devices and mobile apps.

  • Additionally, time shifting and pitch modulation can make voice-controlled systems more robust to different speaking styles.

  • Regularization Techniques such as dropout are beneficial for personalized emotion detection systems, preventing overfitting and ensuring broader generalization. Data augmentation also helps models that need to recognize emotions across diverse user bases.

  • Hyperparameter Tuning plays a role in optimizing performance for dynamic customer interactions, with adjustments in learning rate and batch size improving real-time systems, while tuning the number of epochs balances training time with model accuracy for rapid updates.

  • Evaluating additional metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score is valuable for emotion-sensitive marketing and advanced sentiment analysis, enhancing model targeting and accuracy.

  • Lastly, user feedback integration through active learning ensures that adaptive learning systems remain relevant and accurate by evolving with user interactions.

By adopting these strategies, the model's capabilities can be expanded and refined, leading to better performance and utility across various applications. Continuous improvement through these methods will enhance the model’s ability to understand and respond to diverse emotional cues, thereby increasing its value and effectiveness in practical deployments.
